Industrial materials like concrete and steel are hard to come by in Gando and wood is minimally

06:22.320 --> 06:28.000
available due to deforestation. Thus clay is a material widely used for buildings in the region

06:28.000 --> 06:33.040
for the past several hundred years. However, it's often considered a temporary material as it tends

06:33.040 --> 06:38.640
to wash away under heavy rains. Kerry believed in the use of clay because it's free and locally

06:38.640 --> 06:44.000
available. The reddish earth color fits organically into the surroundings and it has a historical

06:44.000 --> 06:50.640
connection with the people. To improve performance, the clay compound was mixed with about 6% cement

06:50.640 --> 06:55.760
to achieve stable and uniform bricks that are more weather resistant. He also introduced the

06:55.760 --> 07:02.480
portable manually operated press making it possible to easily produce CEBs on site. To address the

07:02.480 --> 07:07.840
sweltering hot conditions where temperatures can often get as hot as 45 degrees celsius,

07:07.840 --> 07:13.360
Kerry pulled the building's roof away from the top of the classroom. This results in a stack effect

07:13.360 --> 07:18.880
that creates a continuous air circulation by drawing in cool air from the windows which rises

07:18.880 --> 07:23.360
through the porphyrated clay ceilings and vents out the perimeter gap below the roof canopy.

07:23.360 --> 07:28.320
This design feature alleviates the need for costly and energy intensive air conditioning,

07:28.320 --> 07:33.920
thus a passively cooled building with a low ecological footprint was created out of necessity.

07:33.920 --> 07:40.160
Francis Kerry's designs are able to achieve durability, usefulness and beauty through paying

07:40.160 --> 07:45.760
close attention to the simplest building block of architecture, the material. He also demonstrates

07:45.760 --> 07:51.520
